Donald Trump won’t win and Joe Biden should not. It’s time for a third option. Here’s why:

First of all, forget about polls, they haven’t been trustworthy for years. For all of the Trump supporters out there, I ask you to take a step back and take off your orange colored glasses. The Democratic Party absolutely wants Donald Trump on the ballot. He is the only candidate they can beat and they know it. Back in March of this year Trump was ahead of DeSantis by 4 points for the Republican nomination. "Magically", the first indictment against him came out in March and his lead began to grow. You might think it was a miscalculation by democrats, but it wasn’t. If it had been, they would not have followed it up with three more indictments, further solidifying Trump’s nomination. How do the Democrats know they can beat Trump, you may ask? Because Trump brings out their vote like nothing else. Most people that vote against Trump are voting at an emotional level not a political one. Democrats also have the advantage of being organized at the ground level and understanding ballot harvesting. They will make sure their voters are registered and make sure they get their ballots sent in. As usual Republicans will rely on in-person voting which will limit participation. So regardless of the current polls, Trump will lose.

Why shouldn’t Joe Biden win? First of all, he is not physically or mentally capable to hold the office. His mental decline is quite obvious even among democrats. While important, that is not the most important reason. Regardless of what you think of Biden, either positive or negative, if he wins he will preside over the fall of the United States as we know it. When Biden beats Trump again the divide that already exists in this country will become too large to bridge. Rightly or wrongly half of this country will decide the election was stolen and will seek retribution. We will not have a peaceful national divorce, we will have a violent civil war. This is not hyperbole, it will be January 6, 2021 times 100.

I am not suggesting that we should let Donald Trump win. Far from it. It's time for Americans to break away from the divisive two-party system and consider alternative options. One such option is a libertarian candidate like myself. The libertarian philosophy prioritizes individual rights and limited government intervention. This perspective could serve as a middle ground between the perceived governmental overreach criticized by conservatives and the personal freedoms championed by liberals. By focusing on personal liberty and fiscal responsibility, as a libertarian candidate, I could bridge the current divide, appealing to Americans who feel disenfranchised by the current system and offer a vision of unity that transcends party lines. For a nation yearning for stability and unity, turning towards a third option, like myself, a libertarian, is exactly the fresh start the U.S. needs.
